# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cloudflare-r2
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cloudflare-r2/amazon-s3] Amazon S3 manages data with an object storage architecture which aims to provide scalability, high availability, and low latency with high durability.
[src:cloudflare-r2/amazon-s3] The basic storage units of Amazon S3 are objects which are organized into buckets.
[src:cloudflare-r2/amazon-s3] Each object is identified by a unique, user-assigned key.
[src:cloudflare-r2/amazon-s3] Buckets can be managed using the console provided by Amazon S3, programmatically with the AWS SDK, or the REST application programming interface.
[src:cloudflare-r2/amazon-s3] Objects can be up to five terabytes in size.
[src:cloudflare-r2/amazon-s3] Requests are authorized using an access control list associated with each object bucket and support versioning which is disabled by default.
[src:cloudflare-r2/amazon-s3] Amazon S3 can be used to replace static web-hosting infrastructure with HTTP client-accessible objects, index document support, and error document support.
[src:cloudflare-r2/amazon-s3] The Amazon AWS authentication mechanism allows the creation of authenticated URLs, valid for a specified amount of time.
[src:cloudflare-r2/amazon-s3] Every item in a bucket can also be served as a BitTorrent feed.
[src:cloudflare-r2/amazon-s3] The Amazon S3 store can act as a seed host for a torrent and any BitTorrent client can retrieve the file.
[src:cloudflare-r2/amazon-s3] This can drastically reduce the bandwidth cost for the download of popular objects.
[src:cloudflare-r2/amazon-s3] A bucket can be configured to save HTTP log information to a sibling bucket; this can be used in data mining operations.
[src:cloudflare-r2/amazon-s3] Various User Mode File System (FUSE)–based file systems for Linux or other Unix-like operating systems can be used to mount an S3 bucket as a file system.
[src:cloudflare-r2/amazon-s3] The semantics of the Amazon S3 file system are not that of a POSIX file system, so the file system may not behave entirely as expected.
[src:cloudflare-r2/amazon-s3] Implementations include Rclone and AWS's own Mountpoint for S3.
[src:cloudflare-r2/amazon-s3] Amazon S3 offers nine different storage classes with different levels of durability, availability, and performance requirements.
[src:cloudflare-r2/amazon-s3] The Amazon S3 Glacier storage classes above are distinct from Amazon Glacier, which is a separate product with its own APIs.
[src:cloudflare-r2/amazon-s3] An object in S3 can be between 0 bytes and 5 TB.
[src:cloudflare-r2/amazon-s3] If an object is larger than 5 TB, it must be divided into chunks prior to uploading.
[src:cloudflare-r2/amazon-s3] When uploading, Amazon S3 allows a maximum of 5 GB in a single upload operation; hence, objects larger than 5 GB must be uploaded via the S3 multipart upload API.
[src:cloudflare-r2/amazon-s3] As of 2025, S3 stores 500 trillion objects, 100s of exabytes of data, serves 200 million requests per second, and peaks at about 1 petabyte per second in bandwidth.
[src:cloudflare-r2/amazon-s3] The broad adoption of Amazon S3 and related tooling has given rise to competing services based on the S3 API.
[src:cloudflare-r2/amazon-s3] These services use the standard programming interface but are differentiated by their underlying technologies and business models.
[src:cloudflare-r2/amazon-s3] A standard interface enables better competition from rival providers and allows economies of scale in implementation, among other benefits.
[src:cloudflare-r2/amazon-s3] Users are not required to go directly to Amazon as several storage providers such as Cloudian, Backblaze B2, Wasabi offer S3-compatible storage with options of on-premises and private cloud deployments.
[src:cloudflare-r2/amazon-s3] Several open-source implementations of S3-compatible object store servers can be self-hosted, such as Garage.
[src:cloudflare-r2/amazon-s3] IBM Cloud Object Storage also offers a cloud-based S3-compatible option of Object Storage.
[src:cloudflare-r2/amazon-s3] Amazon Web Services introduced Amazon S3 in 2006.
[src:cloudflare-r2/amazon-s3] In November 2017, AWS added default encryption capabilities at bucket level.
[src:cloudflare-r2/bandwidth-computing] In computing, **bandwidth** is the maximum rate of data transfer across a given path.
[src:cloudflare-r2/bandwidth-computing] Bandwidth may be characterized as **network bandwidth**, **data bandwidth**, or **digital bandwidth**.
[src:cloudflare-r2/bandwidth-computing] The actual bit rate that can be achieved depends not only on the signal bandwidth but also on the noise on the channel.
[src:cloudflare-r2/bandwidth-computing] The term *bandwidth* sometimes refers to the net bit rate, *peak bit rate*, *information rate*, physical-layer *useful bit rate*, channel capacity, or maximum throughput of a logical or physical communication path in a digital communication system.
[src:cloudflare-r2/bandwidth-computing] For example, bandwidth tests measure the maximum throughput of a computer network.
[src:cloudflare-r2/bandwidth-computing] The maximum rate that can be sustained on a link is limited by the Shannon–Hartley channel capacity for these communication systems, which is dependent on the bandwidth in hertz and the noise on the channel.
[src:cloudflare-r2/bandwidth-computing] The *consumed bandwidth* in bit/s corresponds to achieved throughput or goodput, i.e., the average rate of successful data transfer through a communication path.
[src:cloudflare-r2/bandwidth-computing] The consumed bandwidth can be affected by technologies such as bandwidth shaping, bandwidth management, bandwidth throttling, bandwidth cap, bandwidth allocation (for example bandwidth allocation protocol and dynamic bandwidth allocation), etc.
[src:cloudflare-r2/bandwidth-computing] A bit stream's bandwidth is proportional to the average consumed signal bandwidth in hertz (the average spectral bandwidth of the analog signal representing the bit stream) during a studied time interval.
[src:cloudflare-r2/bandwidth-computing] The asymptotic bandwidth (formally *asymptotic throughput*) for a network is the measure of maximum throughput for a greedy source, for example when the message size (the number of packets per second from a source) approaches close to the maximum amount.
[src:cloudflare-r2/bandwidth-computing] Asymptotic bandwidths are usually estimated by sending a number of very large messages through the network, measuring the end-to-end throughput.
[src:cloudflare-r2/bandwidth-computing] As with other bandwidths, the asymptotic bandwidth is measured in multiples of bits per seconds.
[src:cloudflare-r2/bandwidth-computing] Since bandwidth spikes can skew the measurement, carriers often use the 95th percentile method.
[src:cloudflare-r2/bandwidth-computing] This method continuously measures bandwidth usage and then removes the top 5 percent.
[src:cloudflare-r2/bandwidth-computing] Digital bandwidth may also refer to: multimedia bit rate or average bitrate after multimedia data compression (source coding), defined as the total amount of data divided by the playback time.
[src:cloudflare-r2/bandwidth-computing] Due to the impractically high bandwidth requirements of uncompressed digital media, the required multimedia bandwidth can be significantly reduced with data compression.
[src:cloudflare-r2/bandwidth-computing] The most widely used data compression technique for media bandwidth reduction is the discrete cosine transform (DCT), which was first proposed by Nasir Ahmed in the early 1970s.
[src:cloudflare-r2/bandwidth-computing] DCT compression significantly reduces the amount of memory and bandwidth required for digital signals, capable of achieving a data compression ratio of up to 100:1 compared to uncompressed media.
[src:cloudflare-r2/bandwidth-computing] In web hosting service, the term *bandwidth* is often used to describe the amount of data transferred to or from the website or server within a prescribed period of time, for example *bandwidth consumption accumulated over a month* measured in gigabytes per month.
[src:cloudflare-r2/bandwidth-computing] The more accurate phrase used for this meaning of a maximum amount of data transfer each month or given period is *monthly data transfer*.
[src:cloudflare-r2/bandwidth-computing] A similar situation can occur for end-user Internet service providers as well, especially where network capacity is limited (for example in areas with underdeveloped internet connectivity and on wireless networks).
[src:cloudflare-r2/bandwidth-computing] Edholm's law, proposed by and named after Phil Edholm in 2004, holds that the bandwidth of telecommunication networks double every 18 months, which has proven to be true since the 1970s.
[src:cloudflare-r2/bandwidth-computing] The trend is evident in the cases of Internet, cellular (mobile), wireless LAN and wireless personal area networks.
[src:cloudflare-r2/bandwidth-computing] The MOSFET (metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistor) is the most important factor enabling the rapid increase in bandwidth.
[src:cloudflare-r2/bandwidth-computing] The MOSFET (MOS transistor) was invented by Mohamed M.
[src:cloudflare-r2/bandwidth-computing] Atalla and Dawon Kahng at Bell Labs in 1959, and went on to become the basic building block of modern telecommunications technology.
[src:cloudflare-r2/bandwidth-computing] Continuous MOSFET scaling, along with various advances in MOS technology, has enabled both Moore's law (transistor counts in integrated circuit chips doubling every two years) and Edholm's law (communication bandwidth doubling every 18 months).
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] Cloud storage services may be accessed through a colocated cloud computing service, a web service application programming interface (API) or by applications that use the API, such as cloud desktop storage, a cloud storage gateway or Web-based content management systems.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] Cloud computing is believed to have been invented by J.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] Licklider in the 1960s with his work on ARPANET to connect people and data from anywhere at any time.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] In 1983, CompuServe offered its consumer users a small amount of disk space that could be used to store any files they chose to upload.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] In 1994, AT&T launched PersonaLink Services, an online platform for personal and business communication and entrepreneurship.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] In 2005, Box announced an online file sharing and personal cloud content management service for businesses.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] Alibaba Cloud was launched in September 2009, three years after AWS.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] As of 2024, Gartner ranked cloud storage platforms as follows: AWS, Google, Microsoft, Oracle, Alibaba, IBM, Huawei and Tencent.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] These account for 97% of the global cloud services market.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] This rating was based on ability to execute in market and innovation vision.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] In 2023, 80% of China's technology companies and half of AI LLM companies ran on Alibaba Cloud while in the US dominance belonged to AWS with 31 to 50% share.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] In 2026, Alibaba is scheduled to spend more than 300 million yuan, about $52 billion, on artificial intelligence and cloud infrastructure over the next three years, a figure much larger than the amount spent the previous year.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] Data centers will also be expanding, and AI models like Qwen.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] Alibaba's CEO, Eddie Wu, describes the amount spent as the largest to date on cloud and AI.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] Also, he explained that they expect much of the internal AI workload to run on Alibaba Cloud.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] Spending will include specific items such as GPU-like accelerators and large-scale data centers to support internal workloads and external client functions, underscoring Alibaba's pivot from e-commerce to cloud infrastructure.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] Cloud storage is based on highly virtualized infrastructure and is like broader cloud computing in terms of interfaces, near-instant elasticity and scalability, multi-tenancy, and metered resources.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] Cloud storage services can be used from an off-premises service (Amazon S3) or deployed on-premises (ViON Capacity Services).
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] There are three types of cloud storage: a hosted object storage service, file storage, and block storage.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] Each of these cloud storage types offer their own unique advantages.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] Security of stored data and data in transit may be a concern when storing sensitive data at a cloud storage provider.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] Outsourcing data storage increases the attack surface area.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] Cloud storage is a rich resource for both hackers and national security agencies.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] Because the cloud holds data from many different users and organizations, hackers see it as a very valuable target.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] The number of people with access to the data who could be compromised (e.g., bribed, or coerced) increases dramatically.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] Decryption keys that are kept by the service user, as opposed to the service provider, limit access to data by service provider employees.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] As for sharing multiple data in the cloud with multiple users, a large number of keys has to be distributed to users via secure channels for decryption, also it has to be securely stored and managed by the users in their devices.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] Storing these keys requires rather expensive secure storage.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] To overcome that, key-aggregate cryptosystem can be used.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] It increases the number of networks over which the data travels.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] Instead of just a local area network (LAN) or storage area network (SAN), data stored on a cloud requires a WAN (wide area network) to connect them both.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] By sharing storage and networks with many other users/customers it is possible for other customers to access your data.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] Sometimes because of erroneous actions, faulty equipment, a bug and sometimes because of criminal intent.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] This risk applies to all types of storage and not only cloud storage.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] The risk of having data read during transmission can be mitigated through encryption technology.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] Encryption in transit protects data as it is being transmitted to and from the cloud service.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] Encryption at rest protects data that is stored at the service provider.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] Encrypting data in an on-premises cloud service on-ramp system can provide both kinds of encryption protection.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] There are several options available to avoid security issues.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] One option is to use a private cloud instead of a public cloud.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] Another option is to ingest data in an encrypted format where the key is held within the on-premise infrastructure.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] To this end, access is often by use of on-premise cloud storage gateways that have options to encrypt the data prior to transfer.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] Typically, cloud storage Service Level Agreements (SLAs) do not encompass all forms of service interruptions.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] Exclusions typically include planned maintenance, downtime resulting from external factors such as network issues, human errors like misconfigurations, natural disasters, force majeure events, or security breaches.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] Typically, customers bear the responsibility of monitoring SLA compliance and must file claims for any unmet SLAs within a designated timeframe.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] Customers should be aware of how deviations from SLAs are calculated, as these parameters may vary by other services offered within the same provider.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] These requirements can place a considerable burden on customers.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] Additionally, SLA percentages and conditions can differ across various services within the same provider, with some services lacking any SLA altogether.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] In cases of service interruptions due to hardware failures in the cloud provider, service providers typically do not offer monetary compensation.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] Instead, eligible users may receive credits as outlined in the corresponding SLA.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] Hybrid cloud storage is a term for a storage infrastructure that uses a combination of on-premises storage resources with cloud storage.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] The on-premises storage is usually managed by the organization, while the public cloud storage provider is responsible for the management and security of the data stored in the cloud.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] Hybrid cloud storage can be implemented by an on-premises cloud storage gateway that presents a file system or object storage interface that users can access in the same way they would access a local storage system.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] The cloud storage gateway transparently transfers the data to and from the cloud storage service, providing low latency access to the data through a local cache.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] Hybrid cloud storage can be used to supplement an organization's internal storage resources, or it can be used as the primary storage infrastructure.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] In either case, hybrid cloud storage can provide organizations with greater flexibility and scalability than traditional on-premises storage infrastructure.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] There are several benefits to using hybrid cloud storage, including the ability to cache frequently used data on-site for quick access, while inactive cold data is stored off-site in the cloud.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] This can save space, reduce storage costs and improve performance.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloud-storage] Additionally, hybrid cloud storage can provide organizations with greater redundancy and fault tolerance, as data is stored in both on-premises and cloud storage infrastructure.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare was founded in 2009 by Matthew Prince, Lee Holloway, and Michelle Zatlyn.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] The company went public on the New York Stock Exchange in 2019 under the ticker symbol NET.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare has since expanded its offerings to include edge computing through its Workers platform, a public DNS resolver (1.1.1.1), and a VPN-like service known as WARP.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In recent years, the company has integrated artificial intelligence into its infrastructure, acquiring companies such as Replicate and launching tools to manage AI bots and scrapers.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] According to W3Techs, Cloudflare is used by approximately 21.3% of all websites on the Internet as of January 2026.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] The company has been the subject of controversy regarding its policy of content neutrality.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare has also faced criticism and litigation regarding copyright infringement by websites using its services, notably losing a lawsuit against Japanese publishers in 2025.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] The company experienced significant global outages in late 2025 which disrupted services for major platforms internationally.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare was founded on July 26, 2009, by Matthew Prince, Lee Holloway, and Michelle Zatlyn.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Prince and Holloway had previously collaborated on Project Honey Pot, a product of Unspam Technologies that partly inspired the basis of Cloudflare.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In 2009, the company was venture-capital funded.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] On August 15, 2019, Cloudflare submitted its S-1 filing for an initial public offering on the New York Stock Exchange under the stock ticker NET.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] It opened for public trading on September 13, 2019, at $15 per share.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In 2020, Cloudflare co-founder and COO Michelle Zatlyn was named president.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare has acquired web-services and security companies, including StopTheHacker (February 2014), CryptoSeal (June 2014), Eager Platform Co.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Replicate (November 2025), and Human Native (January 2026).
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Since at least 2017, Cloudflare has used a wall of lava lamps at its San Francisco headquarters as a source of randomness for encryption keys, alongside double pendulums at its London offices and a Geiger counter at its Singapore offices.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] The lava lamp installation implements the Lavarand method, where a camera transforms the unpredictable shapes of the "lava" blobs into a digital image.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In Q4 2022, Cloudflare provided paid services to 162,086 customers.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In October 2024, Cloudflare won a lawsuit against patent troll Sable Networks.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Sable paid Cloudflare $225,000, granted it a royalty-free license to its patent portfolio, and dedicated its patents to the public by abandoning its patent rights.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In November 2025, it was announced Cloudflare had agreed to acquire Replicate, a San Francisco–based platform that enables software developers to run, fine-tune, and deploy open-source machine-learning models via an API without managing infrastructure.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In January 2026, Cloudflare released an analysis regarding BGP routing leaks observed from the Venezuelan state-owned ISP CANTV (AS8048), which occurred on January 2 coincides with the arrest of Nicolás Maduro.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] While some security researchers had speculated that the outages were linked to U.S. cyber operations, Cloudflare's data indicated that the anomalies were consistent with a pattern of "insufficient routing export and import policies" by the ISP rather than malicious external interference.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In January 2026, Cloudflare acquired Human Native, an AI data marketplace that brokers transactions between developers and content creators, for an undisclosed amount.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] On January 16, 2026, Cloudflare acquired The Astro Technology Company, the developers behind the open-source web framework Astro.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In May 2026, Cloudflare announced the elimination of approximately 1,100 positions, around 20 percent of its workforce, in a restructuring the company attributed to the rapid adoption of artificial intelligence tools.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] The announcement coincided with the company's first-quarter 2026 earnings, which reported a record $639.8 million in quarterly revenue, a 34 percent year-over-year increase.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] CEO Matthew Prince stated the cuts were not driven by performance concerns but reflected roles made obsolete by AI, and that Cloudflare expected to employ more people by the end of 2027 than at any point during 2026.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare provides network and security products for consumers and businesses, utilizing edge computing, reverse proxies for web traffic, data center interconnects, and a content distribution network to serve content across its network of servers.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] It supports transport layer protocols TCP, UDP, QUIC, and many application layer protocols such as DNS over HTTPS, SMTP, and HTTP/2 with support for HTTP/2 Server Push.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] As of 2023, Cloudflare handles an average of 45 million HTTP requests per second.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] As of 2024, Cloudflare servers are powered by AMD EPYC 9684X processors.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare also provides analysis and reports on large-scale outages, including Verizon's October 2024 outage.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In April 2026, Cloudflare released an open-source CMS called EmDash, intended to align with serverless and edge-based architecture.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In 2023, Cloudflare launched "Workers AI", a framework allowing for use of Nvidia GPU's within Cloudflare's network.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In 2024, Cloudflare launched a tool that prevents bots from scraping websites.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] To build automatic bot detector models, the company analyzed "AI" bots and crawler traffic.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] The company also launched an "AI" assistant to generate charts based on queries by leveraging "Workers AI".
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare announced plans in September 2024 to launch a marketplace where website owners can sell "AI" model providers access to scrape their site's content.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In March 2025, Cloudflare announced a new feature called "AI Labyrinth", which combats unauthorized "AI" data scraping by serving fake "AI"-generated content to LLM bots.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In July, the company rolled out a permission-based setting to allow websites to automatically block online bots from scraping data and content.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare released AutoRAG into beta in 2025.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] AutoRAG (retrieval augmented generation) creates a vector database of a website's unstructured content to identify relationships between concepts.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] It is part of an initiative with Microsoft, alongside their NLWeb standard, to make websites easier for people and automated systems to query.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare and GoDaddy partnered in April 2026 to enable AI Crawl Control features on GoDaddy hosted websites.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] This would allow site owners to decide how AI bot crawlers interact with their content.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare provides free and paid DDoS mitigation services that protect customers from distributed denial of service (DDoS) attacks.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare received media attention in June 2011 for providing DDoS mitigation for the website of LulzSec, a black hat hacking group.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In March 2013, The Spamhaus Project was targeted by a DDoS attack that Cloudflare reported exceeded 300 gigabits per second (Gbit/s).
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Patrick Gilmore, of Akamai, stated that at the time it was "the largest publicly announced DDoS attack in the history of the Internet".
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] While trying to defend Spamhaus against the DDoS attacks, Cloudflare ended up being attacked as well; Google and other companies eventually came to Spamhaus' defense and helped it to absorb the unprecedented amount of attack traffic.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In 2014, Cloudflare began providing free DDoS mitigation for artists, activists, journalists, and human rights groups under the name "Project Galileo".
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In 2017, it extended the service to electoral infrastructure and political campaigns under the name "Athenian Project".
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] By 2025, more than 2,900 users and organizations were participating in Project Galileo, including 31 US states.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In February 2014, Cloudflare claimed to have mitigated an NTP reflection attack against an unnamed European customer, which it stated peaked at 400 Gbit/s.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In November 2014, it reported a 500 Gbit/s DDoS attack in Hong Kong.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In July 2021, the company claimed to have absorbed a DDoS attack three times larger than any it had previously recorded, which its corporate blog implied was over 1.2 Tbit/s in total.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In February 2023, Cloudflare reported blocking a 71 million request-per-second DDoS attack which "the company says was the largest HTTP DDoS attack on record".
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare blocked the then largest publicly recorded DDoS attack in August 2025, with volumetric attacks peaking at 11.5 terabits per second (tbps).
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] This was surpassed in December 2025 when an Aisuru botnet launched a 31.4 tbps attack, with a requests-per-second rate exceeding 200 million, against multiple companies in the telecommunications sector, a campaign Cloudflare dubbed "The Night Before Christmas".
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In April 2026, Cloudflare released a system designed to let users implement their own custom DDoS mitigation logic, using protocols built on User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In 2017, Cloudflare launched Cloudflare Workers, a serverless computing platform for creating new applications, augmenting existing ones, without configuring or maintaining infrastructure.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] It has expanded to include Workers KV, a low-latency key-value data store; Cron Triggers, for scheduling Cron jobs; and additional tooling for developers to deploy and scale their code across the globe.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In 2020, Cloudflare released a JAMstack platform for developers to deploy websites on Cloudflare's Edge infrastructure, under the name "Pages".
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In 2022, Cloudflare announced an Edge SQL database, D1, which is built on SQLite.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In August 2023, Cloudflare and IBM announced a partnership providing bot management capabilities to protect IBM Cloud customers from malicious bots and automated threats.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] The same month, Cloudflare was hired by SpaceX to boost the performance of Starlink.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In September, the company launched Cloudflare Fonts as a competitor to Google Fonts.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In April 2020, Cloudflare announced it was moving away from using reCAPTCHA in favor of hCaptcha.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In September 2022, Cloudflare began to test Turnstile – an alternative to CAPTCHA.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] The product, instead of presenting a visual CAPTCHA for the user to solve, automatizes the verification process by conducting JavaScript-based checks inside the browser to determine whether the user is a real person or an automated entity.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] The algorithm reportedly uses machine learning to optimize the process.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Through a contract with the Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency, Cloudflare provides registry and authoritative DNS services to the .gov top-level domain.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare also launched Cloudflare for Campaigns in 2020, to offer free cybersecurity tools to political campaigns.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Those tools expanded to include secure email systems in 2025.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In November 2020, Cloudflare announced Cloudflare for Teams, consisting of a DNS resolver and web gateway called "Gateway", and a zero-trust authentication service called "Access".
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare released an Oblivious HTTP relay service in 2022, called Privacy Gateway.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare announced a partnership with PhonePe in January 2023 to secure its mobile payment system.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In February, Cloudflare launched Wildebeest to allow Mastodon users to set up and run their own instances on Cloudflare's infrastructure.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In August 2023, Cloudflare started the Project Cybersafe Schools program as part of a $20 million grant program from Amazon Web Services, making 70 percent of public school districts in the United States eligible for no-cost cybersecurity services.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In March 2024, it announced Firewall for AI to defend applications running large language models (LLMs).
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In September, Cloudflare announced Ephemeral IDs, which identifies fraudulent activity by linking behavior to a client through a short-lived, generated ID, rather than the traditional means of using an IP address.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] The same month, the company also announced all ISP and equipment manufacturers could use its DNS resolvers for free.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare introduced the Cloudforce One threat events platform in March 2025, offering real-time insights into cyberattacks using data gathered from Cloudflare's network.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare's overarching secure access service edge (SASE) platform debuted in October 2020.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare announced the acquisition of Area 1 Security in February 2022, a company who developed a product designed to combat phishing email attacks.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare acquired Nefeli Networks in March 2024, a cloud networking company, co-founded by computer scientist Sylvia Ratnasamy.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In 2019, Cloudflare released a VPN-like service called WARP, and open sourced the custom underlying WireGuard implementation written in Rust.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In January 2021, the company began providing its "Waiting Room" digital queue product for free for COVID-19 vaccination scheduling under the title "Project Fair Shot".
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Project Fair Shot later won a Webby People's Choice Award in 2022 for Event Management under the Apps & Software category.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In March 2023, Cloudflare announced post-quantum cryptography will be made freely and forever available to cloud services, applications and Internet connections.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare released the Speed Brain and Instant Purge features in September 2024, to significantly reduce page load latency by prefetching content, and invalidating cached content in under 150ms.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In 2024, Cloudflare announced plans to launch a new payment method, called Stripe Link, which went into beta in the fall.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Since 2010, Cloudflare has collaborated with the National Center for Missing & Exploited Children to provide data, files, and supplemental investigation from abuse reports observed on its network.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare designed a new NCMEC reporting system in 2024, updating it in 2025 by integrating Cloudflare Workflows and making the CSAM scanning tool accessible globally.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] On June 1, 2012, the hacker group UGNazi compromised some of Cloudflare CEO Matthew Prince's accounts and redirected visitors of the website 4chan to a Twitter account belonging to UGNazi.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] They allegedly used social engineering to trick AT&T support staff into giving them access to Prince's voicemail, then exploited a vulnerability in Cloudflare's use of Google's two-factor authentication system.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Once in control of Prince's email account, UGNazi was able to redirect the 4chan domain through Cloudflare's database.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] From September 2016 until February 2017, a Cloudflare bug nicknamed Cloudbleed leaked sensitive data, including passwords and authentication tokens, from customer websites by sending extra data in response to web requests.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] On November 18, 2025, Cloudflare suffered a major global outage that caused widespread 500 errors, slowing down many platforms, making them unreachable or completely down for users around the world.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Access to WARP, Cloudflare's VPN service, was also briefly disabled in London.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] During the outage, a spokesperson for Cloudflare said the company had seen a "spike in unusual traffic", causing some traffic passing through its network to experience errors.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] At 14:23 UTC, *The Guardian* reported that Cloudflare had released a fix.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] It also reported that maintenance was due at various locations, though this is not known to have caused the outages.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] At 14:42 UTC, Cloudflare informed users on its status page that the fix had been implemented and that it would take some time for remaining post-deployment issues to be fixed.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] A technical postmortem of the incident was released the day following the outage.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare attributed the outage to a change in the configuration of a database, which caused an invalid file to be sent to all servers on the network.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] On December 5, Cloudflare suffered another global outage, which began at 09:00 AM UTC.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] This was the second such outage in three weeks to affect Cloudflare's services.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In January 2026, security researchers disclosed a vulnerability in Cloudflare's Web application firewall (WAF) that allowed attackers to bypass security rules and access origin servers directly.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] The flaw existed in the handling of ACME challenge requests; the logic disabled WAF protections for requests targeting the `/.well-known/acme-challenge/` path without sufficiently verifying if the token matched an active validation attempt.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare patched the vulnerability in October 2025, stating that the issue was a logic flaw rather than a code execution vulnerability and that there was no evidence of exploitation.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare has established a content neutrality policy and opposes the policing of its customers on the basis of free speech unless said customers break the law.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] The company has faced criticism for not banning hate speech websites and websites allegedly connected to terrorism groups.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare has maintained that no law enforcement agency has asked the company to discontinue these services and it closely monitors its obligations under U.S. laws.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In 2022, a research paper by Stanford University found that Cloudflare was a prominent CDN provider, among several other providers, that are disproportionately responsible for serving misinformation websites.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare has come under pressure due to its services being utilized to access far-right content.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare provided DNS routing and DDoS protection for the white supremacist and neo-Nazi website *The Daily Stormer*.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In 2017, after previously refusing to take any action against the website, Cloudflare stopped providing its services to *The Daily Stormer* after an announcement on the website asserted that Cloudflare executives were privately supporting its ideology.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] As a self-described "free speech absolutist", Prince claimed he did not want to repeat the decision, and sought out protections for the company should they be faced with a similar situation in the future.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Prince further addressed the dangers of large companies deciding what is allowed to stay online, a concern shared by a number of civil liberties groups and privacy experts.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] The Electronic Frontier Foundation, a US digital rights group, said that services such as Cloudflare should not be deciding what speech is acceptable and that illegal content should be handled through the legal system.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In 2019, Cloudflare was criticized for providing services to the far-right discussion and imageboard 8chan.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] The message board has been linked to mass shootings in the United States and the Christchurch mosque shootings in New Zealand.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In addition, a number of news organizations including *The Washington Post* and *The Daily Dot* have reported on the existence of child pornography and child sexual abuse discussion boards.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] A Cloudflare representative said that the platform "does not host the referenced websites, cannot block websites, and is not in the business of hiding companies that host illegal content".
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare did not terminate service to 8chan until public and legal pressure mounted in the wake of the 2019 El Paso shooting, in which the associated manifesto was published to 8chan.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In an interview with *The Guardian* immediately after the shooting, CEO Matthew Prince defended Cloudflare's support of 8chan, saying that he had a "moral obligation" to keep 8chan online.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] On August 5, 2019, two days after Prince's interview with The Guardian, Cloudflare terminated service to 8chan.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare explained that 8chan "have proven themselves to be lawless and that lawlessness has caused multiple tragic deaths.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare provided DDoS mitigation and acted as a reverse proxy for Kiwi Farms.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] The site often engages in harassment and doxxing of targets and has been implicated in the suicides of at least three people.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Kiwi Farms also has a reputation for transphobic content, and its users have been accused of swatting vulnerable individuals.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Although Cloudflare was not the primary website host, it did perform critical services to keep Kiwi Farms on-line, both protecting the site from denial-of-service attacks and optimizing content delivery.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In 2022, a campaign was launched by transgender activist Clara Sorrenti, who has previously been targeted by the forum, to pressure Cloudflare into terminating service for Kiwi Farms.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare responded by issuing a statement on its abuse policies and saying it didn't want to set precedent for speech on the internet with its "extraordinary" decision.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] The company also released a blog post and likened its services to that of a public utility, emphasizing that it does not believe in shutting down security services based on content it finds objectionable.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] They acknowledged that while it might be more popular to remove sites that the Cloudflare team finds offensive, it stood by its decision not to do so.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] The company also defended its decision by saying that it donated all earnings from anti-LGBTIQ+ sites to an organization that advocated for LGBTIQ+ rights.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] On September 3, 2022, Cloudflare blocked Kiwi Farms, citing urgent escalating rhetoric against targets of Kiwi Farms, stating that there is an "unprecedented emergency and immediate threat to human life".
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Switter was a social media network for the sex worker community, built by Australia-based company Assembly Four on Mastodon's open-source software, before Cloudflare dropped Switter as a client and ceased services in April 2018, citing terms of service violations.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] This occurred shortly after the passage of FOSTA/SESTA, a set of bills criminalizing websites that facilitate or support sex trafficking in 2018.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] SESTA weakened protections for Internet infrastructure companies and was criticized on free speech grounds due to concerns about disproportionate impact and disruptions to the lives of sex workers.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare said the move was "related to our attempts to understand FOSTA, which is a very bad law and [sets] a very dangerous precedent".
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Assembly Four said that "Given Cloudflare's previous stances of privacy and freedom, as well as fighting alongside the EFF, we had hoped they would take a stand against FOSTA/SESTA".
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In 2015, testimony to the United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs, it was reported that two of the top three online chat forums and nearly forty other web sites belonging to the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant (ISIL) were guarded by Cloudflare.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare has been cited in reports by The Spamhaus Project, an international spam tracking organization, for the high numbers of cybercriminal botnet operations hosted by Cloudflare.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] An October 2015 report found that Cloudflare provisioned 40% of the SSL certificates used by typosquatting phishing sites, which use deceptive domain names resembling those of banks and payment processors to compromise Internet users' banking and other transactions.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare has been criticized for having a conflict of interest by providing DDoS protection to both the operators and victims of "stresser" services.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In 2018, Cloudflare was identified by the European Union's Counterfeit and Piracy Watch List as a "notorious market" which engages in, facilitates, or benefits from counterfeiting and piracy.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] The report noted that Cloudflare hides and anonymizes the operators of 40% of the world's pirate sites, and 62% of the 500 largest such sites, and "does not follow due diligence when opening accounts for websites to prevent illegal sites from using its services".
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In 2020, an Italian court ruled Cloudflare had to block current and future domain names and IP addresses of the pirate IPTV service "IPTV THE BEST" for infringing on Lega Serie A intellectual property.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] At the time, Cloudflare was already blocking 22 domain names in Italy.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Following the December 2024 court ruling, the Spanish LaLiga requested that telephone operators block Cloudflare's IP address ranges in February 2025.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare hosted websites that illegally broadcast soccer matches.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] As a result, the pirate platform DuckVision was shut down before the derby between Real Madrid and Atlético Madrid.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] The platform had 200,000 users and was backed by Cloudflare.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] The blocks affected major legitimate websites, including X, Vimeo, Steam, GitHub, and the Royal Spanish Academy.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare CEO Matthew Prince responded that the company decided to remain providing services to Russian people to counter Russia's attempts to raise a 'digital iron curtain'.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] Cloudflare's Project Galileo, launched in 2014, offers DDoS protection to NGOs for free.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In 2022, they extended free protection to Ukrainian government and telecoms.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] In 2022, Japanese publishers Shueisha, Kodansha, Shogakukan, and Kadokawa Shoten filed a copyright lawsuit against Cloudflare, alleging that the service was distributing data to manga piracy sites and sought an injunction and ¥460 million (US$4 million) in damages.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] On November 19, 2025, a judge ruled in favor of the publishers.
[src:cloudflare-r2/cloudflare] While the ruling recognized approximately ¥3.6 billion (US$24 million) in damages, Cloudflare was ordered to pay a total amount of ¥500 million (US$3.6 million), as the publishers claimed that Cloudflare was only partially responsible for the damages.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] A **content delivery network** (**CDN**) or **content distribution network** is a geographically distributed network of proxy servers and corresponding data centers.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] CDNs provide high availability and performance ("speed") through geographical distribution relative to end users, and arose in the late 1990s to alleviate the performance bottlenecks of the Internet as it was becoming a critical medium.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] Since then, CDNs have grown to serve a large portion of Internet content, including text, graphics and scripts, downloadable objects (media files, software, and documents), applications (e-commerce, portals), live streaming media, on-demand streaming media, and social media services.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] CDNs are a layer in the internet ecosystem.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] Content owners such as media companies and e-commerce vendors pay CDN operators to deliver their content to their end users.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] In turn, a CDN pays Internet service providers (ISPs), carriers, and network operators for hosting its servers in their data centers.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] CDN vendors may cross over into other industries like security, DDoS protection and web application firewalls (WAF), and WAN optimization.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] Content delivery service providers include Akamai Technologies, Cloudflare, Amazon CloudFront, Qwilt (Cisco), Fastly, CDN77, BunnyCDN, EdgeNext, and Google Cloud CDN.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] CDN nodes are usually deployed in multiple locations, often over multiple Internet backbones.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] Benefits include reducing bandwidth costs, improving page load times, and increasing the global availability of content.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] The number of nodes and servers making up a CDN varies, depending on the architecture, some reaching thousands of nodes with tens of thousands of servers on many remote points of presence (PoPs).
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] Others build a global network and have a small number of geographical PoPs.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] Requests for content are typically algorithmically directed to nodes that are optimal in some way.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] When optimizing for performance, locations that are best for serving content to the user may be chosen.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] This may be measured by choosing locations that are the fewest hops or the shortest time to the requesting client, or the highest server performance, to optimize delivery across local networks.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] When optimizing for cost, locations that are the least expensive may be chosen instead.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] In an optimal scenario, these two goals tend to align, as **edge servers** that are close to the end user at the edge of the network may have an advantage in performance and cost.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] Most CDN providers will provide their services over a varying, defined, set of PoPs, depending on the coverage desired, such as United States, Asia-Pacific, International or Global, etc.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] These sets of PoPs can be called "edges", "edge nodes", "edge servers", or "edge networks" as they would be the closest edge of CDN assets to the end user.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] CDN providers profit either from direct fees paid by content providers using their network, or profit from the user analytics and tracking data collected as their scripts are being loaded onto customers' websites inside their browser origin.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] As such these services are being pointed out as potential privacy intrusions for the purpose of behavioral targeting and solutions are being created to restore single-origin serving and caching of resources.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] In particular, a website using a CDN may violate the EU's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR).
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] For example, in 2021 a German court forbade the use of a CDN on a university website, because this caused the transmission of the user's IP address to the CDN, which violated the GDPR.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] CDNs serving JavaScript have also been targeted as a way to inject malicious content into pages using them.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] Subresource Integrity mechanism was created in response to ensure that the page loads a script whose content is known and constrained to a hash referenced by the website author.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] The Internet was designed according to the end-to-end principle.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] This principle keeps the core network relatively simple and moves the intelligence as much as possible to the network end-points: the hosts and clients.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] As a result, the core network is specialized, optimized, and simplified to only forward data packets.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] Content Delivery Networks extend the transport network by distributing on it a variety of intelligent applications employing techniques designed to optimize content delivery.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] The resulting tightly integrated overlay uses web caching, server-load balancing, request routing, and content services.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] Web caches store popular content on servers that have the greatest demand for the content requested.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] These shared network appliances reduce bandwidth requirements, reduce server load, and improve the client response times for content stored in the cache.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] Web caches are populated based on requests from users (pull caching) or based on preloaded content disseminated from content servers (push caching).
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] Server-load balancing uses one or more techniques including service-based (global load balancing) or hardware-based (i.e. layer 4–7 switches, also known as a web switch, content switch, or multilayer switch) to share traffic among a number of servers or web caches.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] Here the switch is assigned a single virtual IP address.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] Traffic arriving at the switch is then directed to one of the real web servers attached to the switch.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] This has the advantage of balancing load, increasing total capacity, improving scalability, and providing increased reliability by redistributing the load of a failed web server and providing server health checks.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] A content cluster or service node can be formed using a layer 4–7 switch to balance load across a number of servers or a number of web caches within the network.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] Request routing directs client requests to the content source best able to serve the request.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] This may involve directing a client request to the service node that is closest to the client, or to the one with the most capacity.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] A variety of algorithms are used to route the request.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] These include Global Server Load Balancing, DNS-based request routing, Dynamic metafile generation, HTML rewriting, and anycasting.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] Proximity—choosing the closest service node—is estimated using a variety of techniques including reactive probing, proactive probing, and connection monitoring.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] CDNs use a variety of methods of content delivery including, but not limited to, manual asset copying, active web caches, and global hardware load balancers.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] Several protocol suites are designed to provide access to a wide variety of content services distributed throughout a content network.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] The Internet Content Adaptation Protocol (ICAP) was developed in the late 1990s to provide an open standard for connecting application servers.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] A more recently defined and robust solution is provided by the Open Pluggable Edge Services (OPES) protocol.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] This architecture defines OPES service applications that can reside on the OPES processor itself or be executed remotely on a Callout Server.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] Edge Side Includes or ESI is a small markup language for edge-level dynamic web content assembly.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] It is fairly common for websites to have generated content.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] It could be because of changing content like catalogs or forums, or because of the personalization.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] This creates a problem for caching systems.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] To overcome this problem, a group of companies created ESI.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] In *peer-to-peer (P2P)* content-delivery networks, clients provide resources as well as use them.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] This means that, unlike client–server systems, the content-centric networks can actually perform better as more users begin to access the content (especially with protocols such as Bittorrent that require users to share).
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] This property is one of the major advantages of using P2P networks because it makes the setup and running costs very small for the original content distributor.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] To incentive peers to participate in the P2P network, web3 and blockchain technologies can be used: participating nodes receive crypto tokens in exchange of their involvement.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] If content owners are not satisfied with the options or costs of a commercial CDN service, they can create their own CDN.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] A private CDN consists of PoPs (points of presence) that are only serving content for their owner.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] These PoPs can be caching servers, reverse proxies or application delivery controllers.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] It can be as simple as two caching servers, or large enough to serve petabytes of content.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] When a private CDN is deployed within a company network, it is also referred as Entreprise CDN or **eCDN**.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] Large content distribution networks may even build and set up their own private network to distribute copies of content across cache locations.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] Such private networks are usually used in conjunction with public networks as a backup option in case the capacity of the private network is not enough or there is a failure which leads to capacity reduction.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] Since the same content has to be distributed across many locations, a variety of multicasting techniques may be used to reduce bandwidth consumption.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] Over private networks, it has also been proposed to select multicast trees according to network load conditions to more efficiently utilize available network capacity.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] The rapid growth of streaming video traffic required large capital expenditures by broadband providers in order to meet this demand and retain subscribers by delivering a sufficiently good quality of experience.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] To address this, telecommunications service providers have begun to launch their own content delivery networks as a means to lessen the demands on the network backbone and reduce infrastructure investments.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] Because they own the networks over which video content is transmitted, telco CDNs have advantages over traditional CDNs.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] They own the last mile and can deliver content closer to the end-user because it can be cached deep in their networks.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] This deep caching minimizes the distance that video data travels over the general Internet and delivers it more quickly and reliably.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] Telco CDNs also have a built-in cost advantage since traditional CDNs must lease bandwidth from them and build the operator's margin into their own cost model.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] In addition, by operating their own content delivery infrastructure, telco operators have better control over the utilization of their resources.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] Content management operations performed by CDNs are usually applied without (or with very limited) information about the network (e.g., topology, utilization etc.) of the telco-operators with which they interact or have business relationships.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] These pose a number of challenges for the telco-operators who have a limited sphere of action in face of the impact of these operations on the utilization of their resources.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] In contrast, the deployment of telco-CDNs allows operators to implement their own content management operations, which enables them to have a better control over the utilization of their resources and, as such, provide better quality of service and experience to their end users.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] In June 2011, StreamingMedia.com reported that a group of TSPs had founded an Operator Carrier Exchange (OCX) to interconnect their networks and compete more directly against large traditional CDNs like Akamai and Limelight Networks, which have extensive PoPs worldwide.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] This way, telcos are building a Federated CDN offering, which is more interesting for a content provider willing to deliver its content to the aggregated audience of this federation.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] It is likely that in a near future, other telco CDN federations will be created.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] They will grow by enrollment of new telcos joining the federation and bringing network presence and their Internet subscriber bases to the existing ones.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] The Open Caching specification by Streaming Video Technology Alliance defines a set of APIs that allows a Content Provider to deliver its content using several CDNs in a consistent way, seeing each CDN provider the same way through these APIs.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] Combining several CDN services allow Content Providers to not rely on a single CDN service, especially concerned to deal with high peak audience during live events.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] There are several ways to allocate traffic to a particular CDN among the list, either client-side CDN selection, or server-side (at the Content Provider's origin) or cloud-side (in the middle, between the content origin and the audience).
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] CDN selection criteria can be performance, availability and cost.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] Traditionally, CDNs have used the IP of the client's recursive DNS resolver to geo-locate the client.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] While this is a sound approach in many situations, this leads to poor client performance if the client uses a non-local recursive DNS resolver that is far away.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] For instance, a CDN may route requests from a client in India to its edge server in Singapore, if that client uses a public DNS resolver in Singapore, causing poor performance for that client.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] Indeed, a recent study showed that in many countries where public DNS resolvers are in popular use, the median distance between the clients and their recursive DNS resolvers can be as high as a thousand miles.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] In August 2011, a global consortium of leading Internet service providers led by Google announced their official implementation of the edns-client-subnet IETF Internet Draft, which is intended to accurately localize DNS resolution responses.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] The initiative involves a limited number of leading DNS service providers, such as Google Public DNS, and CDN service providers as well.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] With the edns-client-subnet EDNS0 option, CDNs can now utilize the IP address of the requesting client's subnet when resolving DNS requests.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] This approach, called end-user mapping, has been adopted by CDNs and it has been shown to drastically reduce the round-trip latencies and improve performance for clients who use public DNS or other non-local resolvers.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] However, the use of EDNS0 also has drawbacks as it decreases the effectiveness of caching resolutions at the recursive resolvers, increases the total DNS resolution traffic, and raises a privacy concern of exposing the client's subnet.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] Virtualization technologies are being used to deploy virtual CDNs (vCDNs) (also known as a software-defined CDN or sd-CDN) with the goal to reduce content provider costs, and at the same time, increase elasticity and decrease service delay.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] With vCDNs, it is possible to avoid traditional CDN limitations, such as performance, reliability and availability since virtual caches are deployed dynamically (as virtual machines or containers) in physical servers distributed across the provider's geographical coverage.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] As the virtual cache placement is based on both the content type and server or end-user geographic location, the vCDNs have a significant impact on service delivery and network congestion.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] To boost performance, delivery to clients from servers can use alternate non-HTTP protocols such as WebRTC and WebSockets.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] In 2017, Addy Osmani of Google started referring to software solutions that could integrate naturally with the Responsive Web Design paradigm (with particular reference to the <picture> element) as **Image CDN**s.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] The expression referred to the ability of a web architecture to serve multiple versions of the same image through HTTP, depending on the properties of the browser requesting it, as determined by either the browser or the server-side logic.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] The purpose of Image CDNs was, in Google's vision, to serve high-quality images (or, better, images perceived as high-quality by the human eye) while preserving download speed, thus contributing to a great User experience (UX).
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] Arguably, the *Image CDN* term was originally a misnomer, as neither Cloudinary nor Imgix (the examples quoted by Google in the 2017 guide by Addy Osmani) were, at the time, a CDN in the classical sense of the term.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] Shortly afterwards, though, several companies offered solutions that allowed developers to serve different versions of their graphical assets according to several strategies.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] Many of these solutions were built on top of traditional CDNs, such as Akamai, CloudFront, Fastly, Edgecast and Cloudflare.
[src:cloudflare-r2/content-delivery-network] At the same time, other solutions that already provided an image multi-serving service joined the Image CDN definition by either offering CDN functionality natively (ImageEngine) or integrating with one of the existing CDNs (Cloudinary/Akamai, Imgix/Fastly).
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Object storage systems allow retention of massive amounts of unstructured data in which data is written once and read once (or many times).
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Object storage is used for purposes such as storing objects like videos and photos on Facebook, songs on Spotify, or files in online collaboration services, such as Dropbox.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] One of the limitations with object storage is that it is not intended for transactional data, as object storage was not designed to replace NAS file access and sharing; it does not support the locking and sharing mechanisms needed to maintain a single, accurately updated version of a file.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Jim Starkey coined the term ***blob*** working at Digital Equipment Corporation to refer to opaque data entities.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] The terminology was adopted for Rdb/VMS.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] *Blob* is often humorously explained to be an abbreviation for *binary large object*.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] According to Starkey, this backronym arose when Terry McKiever, working in marketing at Apollo Computer felt that the term needed to be an abbreviation.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] McKiever began using the expansion *basic large object*.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] This was later eclipsed by the retroactive explanation of blobs as *binary large objects*.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] According to Starkey, "Blob don't stand for nothin'." Rejecting the acronym, he explained his motivation behind the coinage, saying, "A blob is the thing that ate Cincinnatti [*sic*], Cleveland, or whatever", referring to the 1958 science fiction film *The Blob*.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] In 1995, research led by Garth Gibson on Network-Attached Secure Disks first promoted the concept of splitting less common operations, like namespace manipulations, from common operations, like reads and writes, to optimize the performance and scale of both.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] In the same year, a Belgian company – FilePool – was established to build the basis for archiving functions.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Object storage was proposed at Gibson's Carnegie Mellon University lab as a research project in 1996.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Another key concept was abstracting the writes and reads of data to more flexible data containers (objects).
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Fine grained access control through object storage architecture was further described by one of the NASD team, Howard Gobioff, who later was one of the inventors of the Google File System.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Other related work includes the Coda filesystem project at Carnegie Mellon, which started in 1987, and spawned the Lustre file system.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] There is also the OceanStore project at UC Berkeley, which started in 1999 and the Logistical Networking project at the University of Tennessee Knoxville, which started in 1998.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] In 1999, Gibson founded Panasas to commercialize the concepts developed by the NASD team.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Seagate Technology played a central role in the development of object storage.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] This paper was proposed to INCITS T-10 (International Committee for Information Technology Standards) with a goal to form a committee and design a specification based on the SCSI interface protocol.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] This defined objects as abstracted data, with unique identifiers and metadata, how objects related to file systems, along with many other innovative concepts.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Anderson presented many of these ideas at the SNIA conference in October 1999.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] The presentation revealed an IP Agreement that had been signed in February 1997 between the original collaborators (with Seagate represented by Anderson and Chris Malakapalli) and covered the benefits of object storage, scalable computing, platform independence, and storage management.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] One of the design principles of object storage is to abstract some of the lower layers of storage away from the administrators and applications.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Thus, data is exposed and managed as objects instead of blocks or (exclusively) files.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Objects contain additional descriptive properties which can be used for better indexing or management.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Administrators do not have to perform lower-level storage functions like constructing and managing logical volumes to utilize disk capacity or setting RAID levels to deal with disk failure.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Object storage also allows the addressing and identification of individual objects by more than just file name and file path.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Object storage adds a unique identifier within a bucket, or across the entire system, to support much larger namespaces and eliminate name collisions.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Object storage explicitly separates file metadata from data to support additional capabilities.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Object storage provides programmatic interfaces to allow applications to manipulate data.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] At the base level, this includes Create, read, update and delete (CRUD) functions for basic read, write and delete operations.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Some object storage implementations go further, supporting additional functionality like object/file versioning, object replication, life-cycle management and movement of objects between different tiers and types of storage.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Most API implementations are REST-based, allowing the use of many standard HTTP calls.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] The vast majority of cloud storage available in the market leverages an object-storage architecture.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Some notable examples are Amazon S3, which debuted in March 2006, Microsoft Azure Blob Storage, IBM Cloud Object Storage, Rackspace Cloud Files (whose code was donated in 2010 to Openstack project and released as OpenStack Swift), and Google Cloud Storage released in May 2010.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Some distributed file systems use an object-based architecture, where file metadata is stored in metadata servers and file data is stored in object storage servers.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] File system client software interacts with the distinct servers, and abstracts them to present a full file system to users and applications.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Some early incarnations of object storage were used for archiving, as implementations were optimized for data services like immutability, not performance.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] EMC Centera and Hitachi HCP (formerly known as HCAP) are two commonly cited object storage products for archiving.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Another example is Quantum ActiveScale Object Storage Platform.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] More general-purpose object-storage systems came to market around 2008.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] A few object-storage systems support Unified File and Object storage, allowing clients to store objects on a storage system while simultaneously other clients store files on the same storage system.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Other vendors in the area of Hybrid cloud storage are using Cloud storage gateways to provide a file access layer over object storage, implementing file access protocols such as SMB and NFS.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Some large Internet companies developed their own software when object-storage products were not commercially available or use cases were very specific.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Facebook famously invented their own object-storage software, code-named Haystack, to address their particular massive-scale photo management needs efficiently.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Object storage at the protocol and device layer was proposed 20 years ago and approved for the SCSI command set nearly 10 years ago as "Object-based Storage Device Commands" (OSD), however, it had not been put into production until the development of the Seagate Kinetic Open Storage platform.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] The SCSI command set for Object Storage Devices was developed by a working group of the SNIA for the T10 committee of the International Committee for Information Technology Standards (INCITS).
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] T10 is responsible for all SCSI standards.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] One of the first object-storage products, Lustre, is used in 70% of the Top 100 supercomputers and ~50% of the Top 500.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] As of June 16, 2013, this includes 7 of the top 10, including the current fourth fastest system on the list - China's Tianhe-2 and the seventh fastest, the Titan supercomputer at the Oak Ridge National Laboratory.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Object-storage systems had good adoption in the early 2000s as an archive platform, particularly in the wake of compliance laws like Sarbanes-Oxley.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] After five years in the market, EMC's Centera product claimed over 3,500 customers and 150 petabytes shipped by 2007.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Hitachi's HCP product also claims many petabyte-scale customers.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Newer object storage systems have also gotten some traction, particularly around very large custom applications like eBay's auction site, where EMC Atmos is used to manage over 500 million objects a day.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] As of March 3, 2014, EMC claims to have sold over 1.5 exabytes of Atmos storage.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] On July 1, 2014, Los Alamos National Lab chose the Scality RING as the basis for a 500-petabyte storage environment, which would be among the largest ever.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] "Captive" object storage systems like Facebook's Haystack have scaled impressively.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] In April 2009, Haystack was managing 60 billion photos and 1.5 petabytes of storage, adding 220 million photos and 25 terabytes a week.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Facebook more recently stated that they were adding 350 million photos a day and were storing 240 billion photos.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] This could equal as much as 357 petabytes.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Cloud storage has become pervasive as many new web and mobile applications choose it as a common way to store binary data.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] As the storage back-end to many popular applications like Smugmug and Dropbox, Amazon S3 has grown to massive scale, citing over 2-trillion objects stored in April 2013.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Two months later, Microsoft claimed that they stored even more objects in Azure at 8.5 trillion.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] By April 2014, Azure claimed over 20-trillion objects stored.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Windows Azure Storage manages Blobs (user files), Tables (structured storage), and Queues (message delivery) and counts them all as objects.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Coldago Research adopted qualitative and quantitative analysis of the object storage market to rank 13 notable vendors based on technological capabilities, market momentum, and innovation trajectory.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] The 2024 Coldago object storage market leader rating is in alphabetical order: Cloudian, DataCore, Dell EMC, Huawei, IBM, MinIO, Pure Storage, Quantum, and VAST Data.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] In the first version of the OSD standard, objects are specified with a 64-bit partition ID and a 64-bit object ID.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Partitions are created and deleted within an OSD, and objects are created and deleted within partitions.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] There are no fixed sizes associated with partitions or objects; they are allowed to grow subject to physical size limitations of the device or logical quota constraints on a partition.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] An extensible set of attributes describe objects.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Some attributes are implemented directly by the OSD, such as the number of bytes in an object and the modification time of an object.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] There is a special policy tag attribute that is part of the security mechanism.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Other attributes are uninterpreted by the OSD.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] These are set on objects by the higher-level storage systems that use the OSD for persistent storage.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] For example, attributes might be used to classify objects, or to capture relationships among different objects stored on different OSDs.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] A list command returns a list of identifiers for objects within a partition, optionally filtered by matches against their attribute values.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] A list command can also return selected attributes of the listed objects.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Read and write commands can be combined, or piggy-backed, with commands to get and set attributes.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] This ability reduces the number of times a high-level storage system has to cross the interface to the OSD, which can improve overall efficiency.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] A second generation of the SCSI command set, "Object-Based Storage Devices - 2" (OSD-2) added support for snapshots, collections of objects, and improved error handling.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] A snapshot is a point-in-time copy of all the objects in a partition into a new partition.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] The OSD can implement a space-efficient copy using copy-on-write techniques so that the two partitions share objects that are unchanged between the snapshots, or the OSD might physically copy the data to the new partition.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] The standard defines clones, which are writeable, and snapshots, which are read-only.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] A collection is a special kind of object that contains the identifiers of other objects.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] There are operations to add and delete from collections, and there are operations to get or set attributes for all the objects in a collection.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Collections are also used for error reporting.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] If an object becomes damaged by the occurrence of a media defect (i.e., a bad spot on the disk) or by a software error within the OSD implementation, its identifier is put into a special error collection.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] The higher-level storage system that uses the OSD can query this collection and take corrective action as necessary.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] The border between an object store and a key–value store is blurred, with key–value stores being sometimes loosely referred to as object stores.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] A traditional block storage interface uses a series of fixed size blocks which are numbered starting at 0.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Data must be that exact fixed size and can be stored in a particular block which is identified by its logical block number (LBN).
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Later, one can retrieve that block of data by specifying its unique LBN.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] With a key–value store, data is identified by a key rather than a LBN.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] A key might be "cat" or "olive" or "42".
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] It can be an arbitrary sequence of bytes of arbitrary length.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Data (called a value in this parlance) does not need to be a fixed size and also can be an arbitrary sequence of bytes of arbitrary length.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] One stores data by presenting the key and data (value) to the data store and can later retrieve the data by presenting the key.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] This concept is seen in programming languages.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Python calls them dictionaries, Perl calls them hashes, Java, Rust and C++ call them maps, etc.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Several data stores also implement key–value stores such as Memcached, Redis and CouchDB.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Object stores are similar to key–value stores in two respects.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] First, the object identifier or URL (the equivalent of the key) can be an arbitrary string.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Second, data may be of an arbitrary size.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] There are, however, a few key differences between key–value stores and object stores.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] First, object stores also allow one to associate a limited set of attributes (metadata) with each piece of data.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] The combination of a key, value, and set of attributes is referred to as an object.
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Second, object stores are optimized for large amounts of data (hundreds of megabytes or even gigabytes), whereas for key–value stores the value is expected to be relatively small (kilobytes).
[src:cloudflare-r2/object-storage] Finally, object stores usually offer weaker consistency guarantees such as eventual consistency, whereas key–value stores offer strong consistency.
